                \n {"practice":"1","code":"SM-2","subCode":"undefined","explanation":"SM-2 mandates the identification of organizational roles and personnel responsible for security processes, ensuring accountability and clear ownership of security tasks.","context":"In industrial control systems (ICS), defining responsibilities is critical to mitigate risks and ensure compliance with IEC 62443-4-1. This practice applies to all phases of the system lifecycle.","challenges":["Lack of clear role definitions can lead to security gaps. Example: A power plant fails to assign patch management, resulting in unpatched vulnerabilities.","High staff turnover disrupts continuity. Example: A manufacturing site loses its security lead, delaying incident response.","Overlapping responsibilities cause inefficiencies. Example: Both IT and OT teams assume network monitoring, leading to conflicts.","Inadequate training for assigned roles. Example: A SCADA operator lacks training in security protocols, increasing breach risks.","Difficulty in enforcing accountability. Example: A vendor bypasses security checks, blaming unclear responsibilities."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Define roles explicitly in security policies. Example: Assign a 'Security Officer' for access control. Link: Siemens ICS Security Roles Guide.","url":" https://new.siemens.com/global/en/products/automation/industry-software/security-services/industrial-security/ics-security-roles.html","url_description":"Siemens guide on defining ICS security roles, aligned with SM-2."},{"description":"Use RACI matrices to clarify responsibilities. Example: A chemical plant maps 'Responsible' and 'Accountable' for firewall rules. Link: Honeywell RACI Template.","url":" https://www.honeywellprocess.com/library/support/whitepapers/Documents/raci-matrix-ics-security.pdf","url_description":"Honeywell's template for RACI in ICS security."},{"description":"Conduct regular role-based training. Example: Annual drills for incident res